                            <entry>
                    <title>I think the point of CR is to…</title>
                    <link rel="alternate" href="http://coderetreat.org/xn/detail/6456126:Comment:30115"/>
                                        <id>tag:coderetreat.org,2013-11-22:6456126:Comment:30115</id>
                                        <updated>2013-11-22T06:07:53.699Z</updated>
                    
                                            <author>
                            <name>Gabriele Lana</name>
                            <uri>http://coderetreat.org/profile/GabrieleLana</uri>
                        </author>
                    
                    <summary type="html">
                        &lt;p&gt;I think the point of CR is to teach how to practice by doing it. To do that, to practice, the problem you are trying to solve must disappear. The problem it&#039;s an excuse to practice one or more of the programming core skills. That&#039;s why we always use the same problem, that&#039;s why we delete our code at the end of each session. As a host/facilitator/coach I&#039;m happy when they go home knowing why they need to practice and how to practice. As long as you keep the focus on learning how to practice I…&lt;/p&gt;                    </summary>

                                            <content type="html">
                            &lt;p&gt;I think the point of CR is to teach how to practice by doing it. To do that, to practice, the problem you are trying to solve must disappear. The problem it&#039;s an excuse to practice one or more of the programming core skills. That&#039;s why we always use the same problem, that&#039;s why we delete our code at the end of each session. As a host/facilitator/coach I&#039;m happy when they go home knowing why they need to practice and how to practice. As long as you keep the focus on learning how to practice I don&#039;t see a real problem. Only one advice, if you want/need to change the problem don&#039;t choose a &quot;too interesting&quot; problem :-) The GOL is well tuned because it&#039;s interesting/challenging enough to not be boring, but it&#039;s boring enough to let the attendees to focus on practicing :-)&lt;/p&gt;                        </content>
                    
